{{dablink|This article is about followers of indigenous religions in West Africa. For the Northeast Caucasian language, see [[Karata language|Karata]].}}
The '''Kirdi''' are the many [[culture]]s and [[ethnic group]]s who inhabit northwestern [[Cameroon]] and northeastern [[Nigeria]].

The term was applied to various peoples who had not [[Conversion to Islam|converted to Islam]] at the time of colonization and was a [[pejorative]], although some writers have [[Reappropriation|reappropriated]] it.<ref>Steven Nelson, ''From Cameroon to Paris: Mousgoum Architecture In and Out of Africa'' (2007). University of Chicago Press: p. 155.</ref>  The term comes from the [[Kanuri language|Kanuri]] word for [[Paganism|pagan]]; the [[Kanuri people]] are predominantly [[Muslim]].

Estimates of how many groups may be described as Kirdi vary, with estimates ranging from 26 (2007)<ref>Steven Nelson, ''From Cameroon to Paris: Mousgoum Architecture In and Out of Africa'' (2007). University of Chicago Press: p. 155.</ref> to more than 40 (1977).<ref>Gert Chesi and Rudolf Kreuzer. ''The Last Africans'' (1977). Perlinger: p. 18.</ref>

The Bata, [[Fali people|Fali]], Fata, Gemjek, Guidar, Giziga, Hurza, [[Kapsiki people|Kapsiki]], Mada, [[Mafa people|Mafa]], Massa, Matakam, [[Mofu|Mofou]], Mora, [[Musgum people|Mousgoum]], Muyang, Ouldeme, Podoko, [[Toupouri people|Toupouri]], Vame and Zulgo are all considered Kirdi, due to their resistance to Islam. They speak [[Chadic languages|Chadic]] and [[Adamawa languages]].

The first mentioning of Kirdi is by Denham in 1826 (1985:145) who translates the word ''Kerdies'' as "Negroes who have never embraced the Mohammedan faith".

