{{short description|dialect cluster of Quechua}} {{Infobox language |name=Yaru Quechua |nativename= |states=[[Perú]] |speakers=150,000 (partial count) |date=1993–1998 |ref=e18 |speakers2=plus {{sigfig|20,500|1}} Chaupihuaranga (1972 census)<ref name=e18/> |familycolor=American |fam1=[[Quechua languages|Quechua]] |fam2=[[Quechua I|Central]] (Quechua I) |fam3= |lc1= qva |ld1= Ambo-Pasco |lc2= qur |ld2= Chaupihuaranga / Yanahuanca |lc3= qxt |ld3= Santa Ana de Tusi Pasco |lc4= qvn |ld4= [[North Junín Quechua|North Junín]] |glotto=yaru1256 |glottorefname=Yaru Quechua |glotto2=paca1245 |glottoname2=Pacaraos |glottorefname2=Pacaraos Quechua }}
'''Yaru Quechua''' is a [[dialect cluster]] of [[Quechua languages|Quechua]], spoken in the Peruvian provinces of [[Pasco Province|Pasco]] and [[Daniel Alcides Carrión Province|Daniel Alcides Carrión]] and neighboring areas in northern [[Junín Region|Junín]] and Lima department.
The branch of Yaru which has been best described is Tarma Quechua, by Willem F. H. Adelaar in his 1977 ''Tarma Quechua: Grammar, texts, dictionary''. Tarma Quechua is spoken in the districts of Tarma, Huaricolca, Acobamba, La Unión Leticia, Palca, Palcamayo, Tapo, Huasahuasi and San Pedro de Cajas in Junín region, Peru.<ref>{{Cite book | title = Tarma Quechua: Grammar, texts, dictionary | last = Adelaar | first = Willem F. H. | publisher = Peter de Ridder | year = 1977 | isbn = | location = Amsterdam | pages = 20 }}</ref> (See [[North Junín Quechua]].)
